Section section_02 (Chars 8335–11984):
Section Summary: The narrator, a young boy, is expelled from school for not knowing an arithmetic answer and instead goes to work at the Iron Agitator newspaper office, owned by George A. Newett. He starts by washing the press and learning to feed it, earning three dollars a week, and eventually becomes responsible for all presswork, with his wages increasing to six dollars a week. As he gains experience, he is offered higher-paying jobs at other newspapers, including one owned by John D. West, and eventually becomes the acknowledged job printer at the Iron Agitator, earning a man's wages of fifteen dollars a week by the time he is fifteen. The narrator works in challenging conditions, including a cold and poorly heated print shop, and witnesses various events, including the arrival of traveling fakers who try to swindle local merchants. The narrator's career advancement and increasing responsibilities are marked by his growing skills and experience in the print shop.
